<paragraph id="F46BAD144E10FF85FEEBF9F8C77A9136" blockId="0.[329,573,1561,1585]" box="[329,573,1561,1585]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">
<heading id="AF231A784E10FF85FEEBF9F8C77A9136" box="[329,573,1561,1585]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" reason="5">
<collectingRegion id="361063F64E10FF85FEEBF9F8C4DE9136" box="[329,409,1561,1585]" country="American Samoa" name="order" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">ORDER</collectingRegion>
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E10FF85FE03F9FDC77A9136" box="[417,573,1564,1583]" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">GALLIFORMES</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F46BAD144E10FF85FF2DF9A8C7B191C0" blockId="0.[143,759,1609,1754]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">
The living birds classified within the order 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E10FF85FD17F9A8C59B9167" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Galliformes</taxonomicName>
form a large and cosmopolitan group comprising more than 250 species within some 70 genera (
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E10FF85FF34F944C4EB91A2" author="Monroe BL Jr &amp; Sibley CG" box="[150,428,1701,1723]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" refId="ref8292" refString="Monroe BL Jr, Sibley CG. 1990. A world checklist of birds. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press." type="book" year="1990">Monroe &amp; Sibley, 1990</bibRefCitation>
) that are found on almost all continents across the globe (del Hoyo, Elliott &amp;
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BCCEFE9F4E10FF84FF2DF8CDC64594EE" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="228" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" type="description">
<paragraph id="F46BAD144E10FF85FF2DF8CDC4709069" blockId="0.[143,753,1836,1904]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">
<materialsCitation id="44BCA7494E10FF85FF2DF8CDC4709069" collectorName="G. J. Dyke" country="Ireland" location="Department of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="South Dublin">
Corresponding author. 
<collectorName id="5921C8C24E10FF85FED1F8CDC49C9059" box="[371,475,1836,1856]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">G. J. Dyke</collectorName>
, 
<location id="F10BFBCF4E10FF85FE47F8CCC7809059" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:7C7D1C024E10FF84FEEBF9F8C4F59106:F10BFBCF4E10FF85FE47F8CCC7809059" box="[485,711,1836,1856]" country="Ireland" name="Department of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" stateProvince="South Dublin">Department of Zoology</location>
, University College 
<collectingRegion id="361063F64E10FF85FEEFF8A5C4D49041" box="[333,403,1860,1880]" country="Ireland" name="South Dublin" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">Dublin</collectingRegion>
, Belfield, 
<collectingRegion id="361063F64E10FF85FE51F8A5C7709041" box="[499,567,1860,1880]" country="Ireland" name="South Dublin" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">Dublin</collectingRegion>
4, 
<collectingCountry id="8CC3ED844E10FF85FDF6F8A5C7D89041" box="[596,671,1860,1880]" name="Ireland" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">Ireland</collectingCountry>
. E-mail: gdyke@amnh.org
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F46BAD144E10FF84FC85FA0BC4CB9553" blockId="0.[807,1423,1514,1904]" lastBlockId="1.[155,771,196,1567]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="228" pageId="0" pageNumber="227">
Sargatal, 1994). The order contains a number of very familiar taxa, such as pheasants, grouse, Old World quails, partridges, and guineafowls (
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E10FF85FB79F9C9C0199127" box="[1243,1374,1576,1598]" class="Aves" family="Numididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Numididae</taxonomicName>
), as well as a number of somewhat less well known birds including the ‘mound-building’ megapodes, the scrubfowl and brush-turkeys (
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E10FF85FBF7F965C1BF9183" authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1831" box="[1109,1272,1668,1690]" class="Aves" family="Megapodiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Megapodiidae</taxonomicName>
), as well as the guans, chachalacas and curassows (
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E10FF85FA83F943C0CD91A1" box="[1313,1418,1698,1720]" class="Aves" family="Cracidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Cracidae</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E10FF85FC85F920C12091CE" author="Delacour J &amp; Amadon D" box="[807,1127,1729,1751]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" refId="ref6967" refString="Delacour J, Amadon D. 1973. Curassows and related birds. New York: American Museum of Natural History." type="book" year="1973">Delacour &amp; Amadon, 1973</bibRefCitation>
), and New World quails (
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E10FF85FC8DF901C6AC91EF" authorityName="Gould" authorityYear="1844" box="[815,1003,1760,1782]" class="Aves" family="Odontophoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Odontophoridae</taxonomicName>
). Even though the history of galliform classification was reviewed extensively by 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E10FF85FAEBF91FC6BA902A" author="Sibley CG &amp; Ahlquist JE" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" refId="ref8678" refString="Sibley CG, Ahlquist JE. 1990. Phylogeny and classification of birds: a study in molecular evolution. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press." type="book" year="1990">Sibley &amp; Ahlquist (1990)</bibRefCitation>
, it is worth noting that from the inception of avian taxonomy (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E10FF85FB73F8DDC0CC904B" author="Linnaeus C" box="[1233,1419,1852,1874]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" refId="ref7952" refString="Linnaeus C. 1758. Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, 10 th edn. Holmiae: L. Salmii." type="book" year="1758">Linnaeus, 1758</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E10FF85FC85F8BBC6FB9069" author="Huxley TH" box="[807,956,1882,1904]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" pagination="415 - 472" refId="ref7757" refString="Huxley TH. 1867. On the classification of birds; and on the taxonomic value of the modifications of certain of the cranial bones observable in that class. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 1867: 415 - 472." type="journal article" year="1867">Huxley, 1867</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E10FF85FC65F8BBC1189069" author="Garrod AH" box="[967,1119,1882,1904]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" pagination="111 - 123" refId="ref7173" refString="Garrod AH. 1874. On certain muscles of birds and on their value in classification, part II. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 1874: 111 - 123." type="journal article" year="1874">Garrod, 1874</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E10FF85FBC8F8BBC06B9069" author="Furbringer M" box="[1130,1324,1882,1904]" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" pagination="2" refId="ref7126" refString="Furbringer M. 1888. Untersuchungen zur Morphologie und Systematik der Vogel, Vols 1 &amp; 2. Amsterdam: Von Holkema." type="journal article" year="1888">Fürbringer, 1888</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E10FF84FA95F8BBC59397C0" author="Sharpe RB" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="228" pageId="0" pageNumber="227" refId="ref8606" refString="Sharpe RB. 1891. A review of recent attempts to classifiy birds. In: Proceedings of the 2 nd International Ornithological Congress, Budapest." type="book" year="1891">Sharpe, 1891</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF40FF25C43097C0" author="Gadow H" box="[226,375,196,218]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref7149" refString="Gadow H. 1893. Vogel II systematischer thiel. In: Bronn's Klassen und Ordnungen des Thier-Riechs. Leipzig: CF Winter." type="book" year="1893">Gadow, 1893</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FE27FF25C76897C3" author="Beddard FE" box="[389,559,196,218]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref6502" refString="Beddard FE. 1898. The structure and classification of birds. London: Longman, Green &amp; Co." type="book" year="1898">Beddard, 1898</bibRefCitation>
) these birds have consistently been grouped together (yet the composition of families within the order has varied; see 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FD1EFEE0C42A962F" author="Sibley CG &amp; Ahlquist JE" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref8678" refString="Sibley CG, Ahlquist JE. 1990. Phylogeny and classification of birds: a study in molecular evolution. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press." type="book" year="1990">Sibley &amp; Ahlquist, 1990</bibRefCitation>
). Overall, avian anatomists have considered 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FEB8FEDEC4D8964C" box="[282,415,319,341]" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Galliformes</taxonomicName>
to be an osteologically uniform group (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FE88FEBFC4F2966B" author="Lowe PR" box="[298,437,349,371]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref8142" refString="Lowe PR. 1938. Some preliminary notes on the anatomy and systematic position of Afropavo congensis Chapin. In: Proceedings of the 9 th International Ornithological Congress, Rouen." type="book" year="1938">Lowe, 1938</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FE6BFEBCC7C3966A" author="Verheyen R" box="[457,644,349,371]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="1 - 24" refId="ref8766" refString="Verheyen R. 1956. Contribution a l'anatomie et a la systematique des Galliformes. Bulletin Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique 32: 1 - 24." type="journal article" year="1956">Verheyen, 1956</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FD35FEBCC593968B" author="Delacour J" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref6941" refString="Delacour J. 1977. The pheasants of the World, 2 nd edn. Hindhead, UK: World Pheasant Association and Spur Publications." type="book" year="1977">Delacour, 1977</bibRefCitation>
), although much debate has focused on the question of whether the enigmatic hoatzin (
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FDC0FE7AC5A096D7" baseAuthorityName="Statius Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" class="Aves" family="Opisthocomidae" genus="Opisthocomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opisthocomiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hoazin">
<emphasis id="C6A071064E11FF84FDC0FE7AC5A096D7" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">Opisthocomus hoazin</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) should also be classified within the order (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF39FE39C42B96F4" author="Furbringer M" box="[155,364,472,494]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="2" refId="ref7126" refString="Furbringer M. 1888. Untersuchungen zur Morphologie und Systematik der Vogel, Vols 1 &amp; 2. Amsterdam: Von Holkema." type="journal article" year="1888">Fürbringer, 1888</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FE24FE39C70496F4" author="Seebohm H" box="[390,579,472,494]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref8571" refString="Seebohm H. 1890. The classification of birds: an attempt to classify and subclasses, orders, suborders and some of the families of existing birds. London: R. Porter." type="book" year="1890">Seebohm, 1890</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FDFFFE39C7B896F4" author="Gadow H" box="[605,767,472,494]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref7149" refString="Gadow H. 1893. Vogel II systematischer thiel. In: Bronn's Klassen und Ordnungen des Thier-Riechs. Leipzig: CF Winter." type="book" year="1893">Gadow, 1893</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF39FE16C4159515" author="Shufeldt RW" box="[155,338,503,525]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="833 - 857" refId="ref8633" refString="Shufeldt RW. 1904. An arrangement of the families and higher groups of birds. American Naturalist 38: 833 - 857." type="journal article" year="1904">Shufeldt, 1904</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FECEFE16C7ED9515" author="Sibley CG &amp; Ahlquist JE" box="[364,682,503,525]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="1 - 13" refId="ref8657" refString="Sibley CG, Ahlquist JE. 1973. The relationships of the Hoatzin. Auk 90: 1 - 13." type="journal article" year="1973">Sibley &amp; Ahlquist, 1973</bibRefCitation>
, 1990; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF39FDF4C4059533" author="Cracraft J" box="[155,322,533,555]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="681 - 714" refId="ref6721" refString="Cracraft J. 1981. Towards a phylogenetic classification of the Recent birds of the world (Class Aves). Auk 98: 681 - 714." type="journal article" year="1981">Cracraft, 1981</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FEEDFDF4C7689533" author="Mindell DP &amp; Sorenson MD &amp; Huddleston CJ &amp; Miranda HC Jr &amp; Knight A &amp; Sawchuk SJ &amp; Yuri T" box="[335,559,533,555]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref8236" refString="Mindell DP, Sorenson MD, Huddleston CJ, Miranda HC Jr, Knight A, Sawchuk SJ, Yuri T. 1997. Phylogenetic relationships among and within select avian orders based on mitochondrial DNA. In: Mindell DP, ed. Avian molecular systematics and evolution. New York: Academic Press." type="book" year="1997">
Mindell 
<emphasis id="C6A071064E11FF84FE12FDF7C4A79533" box="[432,480,533,555]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">et al</emphasis>
., 1997
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FD99FDF4C5939550" author="Hughes JM &amp; Baker AJ" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="1300 - 1307" refId="ref7721" refString="Hughes JM, Baker AJ. 1999. Phylogenetic relationships of the enigmatic hoatzin (Opisthocomus hoazin) resolved using mitochondrial and nuclear gene sequences. Molecular Biology and Evolution 16: 1300 - 1307." type="journal article" year="1999">Hughes &amp; Baker, 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF42FDD5C4C79553" author="Hughes JM" box="[224,384,564,586]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="263 - 307" refId="ref7689" refString="Hughes JM. 2000. Monophyly and phylogeny of cuckoos (Aves, Cuculidae) inferred from osteological characters. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 130: 263 - 307." type="journal article" year="2000">Hughes, 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F46BAD144E11FF84FF11FDB2C64594EE" blockId="1.[155,771,196,1567]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">
From the results of their now classic DNAhybridization study, 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FE2FFD90C7F4959E" author="Sibley CG &amp; Ahlquist JE" box="[397,691,625,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref8678" refString="Sibley CG, Ahlquist JE. 1990. Phylogeny and classification of birds: a study in molecular evolution. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press." type="book" year="1990">Sibley &amp; Ahlquist (1990)</bibRefCitation>
recognized two distinct lineages within their superorder 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FF39FD4EC47B95DC" box="[155,316,687,709]" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="superOrder" superOrder="Gallomorphae">Gallomorphae</taxonomicName>
(equivalent to the ‘traditional’ order 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FF39FD2CC46795FA" box="[155,288,717,739]" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Galliformes</taxonomicName>
of most earlier workers), 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FDE4FD2CC79795FA" box="[582,720,717,739]" class="Aves" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Craciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Craciformes</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FF39FD0DC467941B" box="[155,288,748,770]" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Galliformes</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="6CEFB1914E11FF84FE93FD0DC4C2941B" box="[305,389,748,770]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[142,220,1859,1878]" captionTargetBox="[468,1115,1111,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-104@2.[398,1163,1103,1823]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. Two previous hypotheses for the internal relationships of Galliformes: A, Sibley &amp; Ahlquist (1990: fig. 357). B, Johnsgard (1986: fig. 3; reproduced with permission, Oxford University Press)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437425" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437425/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Representing a departure from the majority of older avian classifications, 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FD3EFCEAC4099426" author="Sibley CG &amp; Ahlquist JE" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref8678" refString="Sibley CG, Ahlquist JE. 1990. Phylogeny and classification of birds: a study in molecular evolution. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press." type="book" year="1990">Sibley &amp; Ahlquist (1990)</bibRefCitation>
removed 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FE62FCC8C7189426" authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1831" box="[448,607,809,831]" class="Aves" family="Megapodiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Megapodiidae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FD3EFCC8C6469426" box="[668,769,809,831]" class="Aves" family="Cracidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Cracidae</taxonomicName>
as a separate clade distinct from the remaining ‘phasianoid’ taxa (
<figureCitation id="6CEFB1914E11FF84FEF0FC86C4E19464" box="[338,422,871,893]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[142,220,1859,1878]" captionTargetBox="[468,1115,1111,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-104@2.[398,1163,1103,1823]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. Two previous hypotheses for the internal relationships of Galliformes: A, Sibley &amp; Ahlquist (1990: fig. 357). B, Johnsgard (1986: fig. 3; reproduced with permission, Oxford University Press)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437425" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437425/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Most older classifications, albeit not couched within a strictly phylogenetic context, had at least implied a sequence of derivation for these birds within a single, distinct grouping (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF39FC00C40D94EE" author="Verheyen R" box="[155,330,993,1015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="1 - 24" refId="ref8766" refString="Verheyen R. 1956. Contribution a l'anatomie et a la systematique des Galliformes. Bulletin Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique 32: 1 - 24." type="journal article" year="1956">Verheyen, 1956</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FEF7FC00C4CA94EE" author="Verheyen R" box="[341,397,993,1015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref8795" refString="Verheyen R. 1961. A new classification for the non-passerine birds of the world. Bulletin Institut Royal des Sciences Naturelles de Belgique 37: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="1961">1961</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FE3BFC00C71394EF" author="Johnsgard PA" box="[409,596,993,1015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref7800" refString="Johnsgard PA. 1973. Grouse and quails of North America. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press." type="book" year="1973">Johnsgard, 1973</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FDFDFC00C7D094EE" author="Johnsgard PA" box="[607,663,993,1015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref7819" refString="Johnsgard PA. 1986. The pheasants of the world. New York: Oxford University Press." type="book" year="1986">1986</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="6CEFB1914E11FF84FD01FC00C7B294EE" box="[675,757,993,1015]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[142,220,1859,1878]" captionTargetBox="[468,1115,1111,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-104@2.[398,1163,1103,1823]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. Two previous hypotheses for the internal relationships of Galliformes: A, Sibley &amp; Ahlquist (1990: fig. 357). B, Johnsgard (1986: fig. 3; reproduced with permission, Oxford University Press)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5437425" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5437425/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BCCEFE9F4E11FF84FF11FBE1C4F59106" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="F46BAD144E11FF84FF11FBE1C4F59106" blockId="1.[155,771,196,1567]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">
<collectingRegion id="361063F64E11FF84FF11FBE1C5B0930F" box="[179,247,1024,1046]" country="American Samoa" name="order" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">Order</collectingRegion>
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FF5CFBE1C4C4930F" box="[254,387,1024,1046]" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Galliformes</taxonomicName>
generally has been considered to be one of the more basal clades of modern birds (= Neornithes 
<emphasis id="C6A071064E11FF84FE86FBDFC424934A" box="[292,355,1086,1107]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FECFFBDCC75F934A" author="Cracraft J" box="[365,536,1085,1107]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="383 - 399" refId="ref6749" refString="Cracraft J. 1986. The origin and early diversification of birds. Paleobiology 12: 383 - 399." type="journal article" year="1986">Cracraft, 1986</bibRefCitation>
). Current classifications (e.g. del 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FE9AFBBDC4B1936B" author="Hoyo J &amp; Elliott A &amp; Sargatal J" box="[312,502,1116,1138]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="434 - 557" refId="ref7543" refString="del Hoyo J, Elliott A, Sargatal J. 1994. Galliformes. In: del Hoyo J, Elliott A, Sargatal J, eds. Handbook of the birds of the world, Vol. 2. Barcelona: Lynx Ediciones, 434 - 557." type="book chapter" year="1994">
Hoyo 
<emphasis id="C6A071064E11FF84FED8FBBCC4ED9368" box="[378,426,1116,1138]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="228">et al</emphasis>
., 1994
</bibRefCitation>
) suggest that the order comprises at least five distinct families, namely 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FF39FB78C47D93B6" authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1831" box="[155,314,1177,1199]" class="Aves" family="Megapodiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Megapodiidae</taxonomicName>
(megapodes and relatives), 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FD21FB78C64593B6" box="[643,770,1177,1199]" class="Aves" family="Numididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Numididae</taxonomicName>
(guineafowl), 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FE9BFB59C48193D7" authorityName="Horsfield" authorityYear="1821" box="[313,454,1208,1230]" class="Aves" family="Phasianidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Phasianidae</taxonomicName>
(pheasants and relatives), 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FF39FB36C41593F4" authorityName="Gould" authorityYear="1844" box="[155,338,1239,1261]" class="Aves" family="Odontophoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Odontophoridae</taxonomicName>
(New World quails), and 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FD3FFB36C64593F4" box="[669,770,1239,1261]" class="Aves" family="Cracidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Cracidae</taxonomicName>
(curassows and relatives; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FE74FB17C7CE9212" author="Wetmore A" box="[470,649,1269,1291]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="1 - 37" refId="ref8825" refString="Wetmore A. 1960. A classification for the birds of the world. Smithsonian Miscellaneous Collections 139: 1 - 37." type="journal article" year="1960">Wetmore, 1960</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FD39FB14C5939230" author="Cracraft J" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="681 - 714" refId="ref6721" refString="Cracraft J. 1981. Towards a phylogenetic classification of the Recent birds of the world (Class Aves). Auk 98: 681 - 714." type="journal article" year="1981">Cracraft, 1981</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF45FAF5C7569233" author="Sibley CG &amp; Ahlquist JE" box="[231,529,1300,1322]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref8678" refString="Sibley CG, Ahlquist JE. 1990. Phylogeny and classification of birds: a study in molecular evolution. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press." type="book" year="1990">Sibley &amp; Ahlquist, 1990</bibRefCitation>
). Most often, 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FD60FAF5C5AF9250" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Galliformes</taxonomicName>
(‘landfowl’) have been placed within a basal neornithine clade along with the 
<taxonomicName id="33D4D6974E11FF84FDCBFAB0C645927E" box="[617,770,1361,1383]" class="Aves" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anseriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Anseriformes</taxonomicName>
(‘waterfowl’) that has been termed Galloanserae or Galloanserimorphae (dependant on implied rank; e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF6BFA4CC43592DB" author="Cracraft J" box="[201,370,1453,1475]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" refId="ref6769" refString="Cracraft J. 1988. The major clades of birds. In: Benton MJ, ed. The phylogeny and classification of the Tetrapods, Vol. 1: amphibians, reptiles, birds. Oxford: Systematics Association." type="book" year="1988">Cracraft, 1988</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FEDDFA4CC71392DA" author="Dzerzhinsky FY" box="[383,596,1453,1475]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="325 - 336" refId="ref7017" refString="Dzerzhinsky FY. 1995. Evidence for common ancestry of the Galliformes and Anseriformes. Courier Forschungsintut Senckenberg 181: 325 - 336." type="journal article" year="1995">Dzerzhinsky, 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FDC3FA4CC7B892DB" author="Livezey BC" box="[609,767,1453,1475]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="361 - 428" refId="ref7997" refString="Livezey BC. 1997. A phylogenetic analysis of basal Anseriformes, the fossil Presbyornis and the interordinal relationships of waterfowl. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 121: 361 - 428." type="journal article" year="1997">Livezey, 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FF39FA2DC4A392F8" author="Groth JG &amp; Barrowclough GF" box="[155,484,1484,1506]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="115 - 123" refId="ref7206" refString="Groth JG, Barrowclough GF. 1999. Basal divergences in birds and the phylogenetic utility of the nuclear RAG- 1 gene. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 12: 115 - 123." type="journal article" year="1999">Groth &amp; Barrowclough, 1999</bibRefCitation>
; see 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FDBAFA2DC64592F8" author="Zusi RL &amp; Livezey BC" box="[536,770,1484,1506]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="157 - 193" refId="ref8872" refString="Zusi RL, Livezey BC. 2000. Homology and phylogenetic implications of some enigmatic cranial features in galliform and anseriform birds. Annals of the Carnegie Museum of Natural History 69: 157 - 193." type="journal article" year="2000">Zusi &amp; Livezey, 2000</bibRefCitation>
for further commentaries; see also 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FD87FA0AC7869118" author="Ericson PGP" box="[549,705,1515,1537]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="195 - 202" refId="ref7041" refString="Ericson PGP. 1996. The skeletal evidence for a sister-group relationship of anseriform and galliform birds - a critical evaluation. Journal of Avian Biology 27: 195 - 202." type="journal article" year="1996">Ericson, 1996</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="9045D0E54E11FF84FD69FA0AC6459119" author="Ericson PGP" box="[715,770,1515,1536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="228" pagination="429 - 483" refId="ref7073" refString="Ericson PGP. 1997. Systematic relationships of the Paleogene family Presbyornithidae (Aves: Anseriformes). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 21: 429 - 483." type="journal article" year="1997">1997</bibRefCitation>
for an alternative view).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
